@jkff thanks for the review. I understand your concern about changes that are not strictly necessary being part of this PR. However, as you know this is not really a standalone change but part of an originally larger diff that aims to enable SplittableDoFn. It was discussed later to submit these changes separately and I already spent a good amount of time removing all the other splittable specific pieces. I think before spending even more time extracting the as you rightly point out unused code, I would rather return to the original plan and submit an even larger PR for the entire splittable feature. @kennknowles would like to have your opinion on that as well.

I am a bit conflicted here, because on one hand I'm very happy with progress on SDF and on removing the ugly remnants of OldDoFn, but on the other hand I'm not comfortable LGTMing code that I do not fully understand; plus there's concerns that Kenn expressed about clean rollbacks/cherrypicks, and general hygiene of file history.

For me, progress on the features in this case is sufficiently important that I also won't block on some of these concerns, but there are a few things that I think are simple enough to address, and would greatly improve the state of this PR, so I would prefer to see them addressed:

- As Kenn says, some of the large chunks of code here here seem easy to remove from the PR using git add -p. That would significantly reduce the size of this PR and make it easier to review.
- I'd really appreciate if you edited the PR description to explain the major changes you did here, and why. That also would make it easier to review for me (I would be able to review it much faster and with much higher quality); and I found that when I do this myself, I often find that there are things I missed, so it's good for code quality too.

I'm fine with the current phrasing, though I'd replace "may" with "should". Even though in practice runners will gracefully treat multiple things as "unknown", I'd prefer to explicitly advertise only one of those things.
@diptikul Now that PR 2193 is merged, let's make sure this PR gets rebased onto those changes - basically, we should see all the old commits from the former PRs disappear from this PR.

@kennknowles @jkff I addressed the comments and updated the PR description. BTW git add -p is very useful if the hunks are self contained, but not for cases where removal leaves behind unused import statements, for example. Overall, as much as I agree with the ideal situation, my time is also limited and I would like to spend it on those things that really benefit the Apex runner. I could have probably fixed a couple minor JIRAs instead of shifting hunks of code between PRs.
